(2135, 1, '2022-10-05 08:31:05', '2022-10-05 08:31:05', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sheldon Silverstein was born in Chicago on September 25, 1930. He was an American writer, poet, cartoonist, songwriter, and playwright.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During his childhood, Silverstein had a desire to write, and that\'s when he developed his writing style and skills. In the 1950\'s, he served in the U.S military in Korea and Japan, and he got a job as a cartoonist for the <em>Pacific Stars and Stripes</em>. After his service, he sold hotdogs at Chicago parks and continued to write cartoons for newspapers and national magazines.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1963 he published his first book, <em><a href=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/lafcadio-the-lion-who-shot-back/\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/lafcadio-the-lion-who-shot-back/\">Lafcadio, the Lion Who Shot Back</a></em>. Although, it was never in his plans to write or draw for children, a friend convinced him to follow this path. In 1964, <em><a href=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/the-giving-tree/\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/the-giving-tree/\">The Giving Tree</a></em>, which would become his most successful book, was published. It was four years before Silverstein found someone who would publish <em>The Giving Tree.</em> Some publishers thought the book was too sad to publish. In an interview with <em>Chicago Tribune</em>, Shel said, \"Because life, you know, has pretty sad endings. You don\'t have to laugh it up even if most of my stuff is humorous.\" <a href=\"http://www.shelsilverstein.com/about-shel/\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"http://www.shelsilverstein.com/about-shel/\">(ShelSilverstein.com)</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\"><!-- wp:column {\"width\":\"33.33%\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.33%\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1969, Silverstein released the song \"A Boy Named Sue\", which became a hit for Johnny Cash. Shel continued writing children\'s books; <em><a href=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/the-missing-piece/\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/the-missing-piece/\">The Missing Piece</a></em> (1976), and <em><a href=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/the-missing-piece-meets-the-big-o/\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/the-missing-piece-meets-the-big-o/\">The Missing Piece Meets the Big O</a></em> (1981). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Silverstein first released his collection of poems in <em><a href=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/where-the-sidewalk-ends/\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/where-the-sidewalk-ends/\">Where the Sidewalk Ends</a></em> (1974). <em><a href=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/a-light-in-the-attic/\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/a-light-in-the-attic/\">A Light in the Attic</a></em> (1981) is his second book of poems, followed by the third book, <em><a href=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/falling-up/\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/book/falling-up/\">Falling Up</a></em> (1996). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column {\"width\":\"66.66%\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\"><!-- wp:image {\"id\":2110,\"width\":428,\"height\":419,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img src=\"https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/shel-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2110\" width=\"428\" height=\"419\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Silverstein had two children, Shoshannna, born in 1970, and Matthew, born in 1984. Shel Silverstein died in May 1999, in his home in Key West, Florida. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator {\"className\":\"is-style-wide\"} -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity is-style-wide\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Reviews</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:shortcode -->\n[wpb-random-posts]\n<!-- /wp:shortcode -->', 'About the Author', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-10-05 08:31:05', '2022-10-05 08:31:05', '', 2, 'https://fwolfeil.bitlampsites.com/wpd/new-final/?p=2135', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
